'''Artur Asilbekovich Beterbiev''' ({{langx|ce|Бетербиев Асильбекан Артур}}; {{langx|ru|Артур Асильбекович Бетербиев}}; born 21 January 1985) is a Russian and Canadian [[professional boxer]].<ref name="guardian">{{cite news |last1=Zidan |first1=Karim |title=Artur Beterbiev: Kadyrov looms over Chechen-born star's unification bout |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2022/jun/18/artur-beterbiev-ramzan-kadyrov-connections-joe-smith-fight |access-date=19 June 2022 |work=the Guardian |date=18 June 2022 |language=en}}</ref><ref name="reuters">{{cite news |last1=Baldwin |first1=Alan |title=Beterbiev set to fight as Canadian after Russian ban, says WBC boss |url=https://www.reuters.com/lifestyle/sports/beterbiev-set-fight-canadian-after-russian-ban-says-wbc-boss-2022-04-20/ |access-date=19 June 2022 |work=Reuters |date=20 April 2022 |language=en}}</ref> He held the [[undisputed championship (boxing)|undisputed]]{{efn|Four-belt era: [[World Boxing Association]] (WBA) ([[WBA (Super)|Super version]]), [[World Boxing Council]] (WBC), [[International Boxing Federation]] (IBF), and [[World Boxing Organization]] (WBO) titles.}}, and the ''[[The Ring (magazine)|Ring]]'' magazine world [[light-heavyweight]] championship between 2024 and February 2025. He also held the [[International Boxing Organization]] (IBO) title during his reign as champion.

Beterbiev is the first boxer to become the undisputed light-heavyweight champion since [[Roy Jones Jr.]] last held that distinction in 2002,{{efn|Three-belt era: [[World Boxing Association]] (WBA) ([[WBA (Unified)|Unified version]]), [[World Boxing Council]] (WBC), [[International Boxing Federation]] (IBF) titles.}} and is the first to do so in the "four-belt" era.<ref>2024-10-12 (Santoliquito, Joseph). [https://www.ringtv.com/714157-artur-beterbiev-outpoints-dmitry-bivol-makes-history-as-first-undisputed-light-heavy-champ-of-four-belt-era/ "Artur Beterbiev Outpoints Dmitry Bivol, Makes History as First Undisputed Light Heavy Champ of Four-belt Era"]. ''[[The Ring (magazine)|The Ring]]''. Retrieved 2024-10-17.</ref>

As an [[amateur boxing|amateur]], Beterbiev won a light-heavyweight silver medal at the [[2007 World Amateur Boxing Championships|2007 World Championships]], gold at the [[2008 Boxing World Cup|2008 World Cup]] and [[2009 World Amateur Boxing Championships|2009 World Championships]], as well as gold at the [[2006 European Amateur Boxing Championships|2006]] and [[2010 European Amateur Boxing Championships|2010 European Championships]]. He also reached the [[heavyweight]] quarter-finals at the [[2012 Olympics]].

He is particularly known for his exceptional punching power, having won the first 20 of his 21 professional fights by [[knockout]] or [[technical knockout|stoppage]] since debuting in 2013.<ref>Idec, Keith (23 December 2016). [http://www.boxingscene.com/beterbiev-stops-prieto-first-round-keep-ko-streak-intact--112049 "Beterbiev Stops Prieto in First Round to Keep KO Streak Intact"]. BoxingScene. Retrieved 24 December 2016.</ref>

